Demographics
With a population exceeding 220 million, Nigeria faces enormous demand on its health system. Primary health centres — the most numerous facility type — are designed to serve communities of approximately 5,000 people, though many are under-resourced or non-functional. Nigeria has a physician density of approximately 3.8 per 10,000 population, though distribution is highly skewed toward urban centres. Brain drain of health workers remains a significant systemic challenge. ## Services {#services}
Nigerian health facilities deliver a broad range of services including outpatient and inpatient care, malaria diagnosis and treatment (Nigeria bears the highest global malaria burden, accounting for ~27% of global cases), HIV/AIDS services, maternal and child health (ANC, skilled delivery, postnatal care), immunization under the National Programme on Immunization, TB services, and nutrition support. The private sector plays a large role in service delivery, particularly in urban areas.
